John Edward: Knowledge of languages for world citizens is essential
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This has continued with further outstanding test results in 2018 and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of care for their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as a world citizen.
As an educational sector, which can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and popular in schools as elective subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak with him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current audit results of this year show that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages achieved grade A in the higher examinations.
From the data collected from 74 SCIS member schools, 72 percent of students in Mandarin achieved grade A in higher education, while 72 percent of students who learned German, 69 percent of students who learned French, and 63 percent of students who learned Spanish also achieved grade A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that will undoubtedly need children and young people in the future.
Languages are today regarded as elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers mentioned for the problems of filling open jobs were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future career.
As more and more open jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such a lifelong ability in the future.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, multilingual people will automatically give a head start to competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today's children that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak several languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will be taught, which are considered by 2020 to be the most important ones for the United Kingdom, for example Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever the interests of your child lie, in independent schools there will always be a number of languages with appropriately specialized teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future may look like.
At this time, in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country. This must therefore be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication capability'.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il fout bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent School.
