Harvard students learn in a course to sleep enough
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students get more sleep in primary school this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture to stay awake with caffeine and learn about the whole night.
One scientist has found that students at the world's leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to paying attention.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and Specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital and is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
After their words no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
This year's first course explained to the students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Managing Director of the University's Health Services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after she found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, the students see the picture of a room in a residential home and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They get information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as about the effects of sleep deprivation on the sporty performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to reflect on their daily routine by means of an interactive symbols map of the university site.
“We know that it will not change the behaviour of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how smoking affects your health," Czeisler added.
The pride in pushing a "night shift" is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-growing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. He had completed one of his courses in Harvard last year.
He said that the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to press for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study programme before they begin their studies at the competitive university.
At Professor Czeisler's recommendation, students should be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light", which is based on electronic screens and LED lighting and can remove the circadian rhythm.
