HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14°% in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
Some 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
In contrast to the past, the transfer took place in the vast majority of new cases through sexual intercourse.
Up to now, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way had almost been reduced to zero, reported Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
In comparison, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
The transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against members of the LGBT community should be widespread.
Due to the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection in sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised, among other things, general access to HIV medicines to address the problem.
