In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee suggested that the intention behind Inrupt be the "world domination".
"We need to become active now," he said on the topic of startup.
"It is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology so that users can create their own personal online data storage or a POD.
It can include contact lists, to-dos lists, a calendar, a music library and other tools for the private and corporate sector.
Similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all content is available in a browser and at the same time.
The special feature of the personal online data storage is that the user can decide only who can access which data.
The company describes this concept as personal strengthening and development of data.
According to the CEO of the company John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company uses resources, processes and corresponding capabilities so that Solid is available to all.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, some developers who have been hired to work on this project, as well as a community of volunteer programmers. Furthermore, a security platform acquired by IBM is used.
At the beginning of this week, technology developers worldwide can create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee announced that he and his team will not exchange views with Facebook and Google on whether a comprehensive change is to be made in order to completely reshape their entire business models overnight.
"We are not asking for their permission."
In a contribution on medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt has the task of providing commercial energy generation and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new, solid-based web.
In 1994, Berners-Lee redesigned the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been a major player in the debate on net neutrality.
Even with the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely confident about this new era of the Web," he added.
