National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In a property in the Scottish Highlands, new research will be carried out to show how bats use the landscape in food search.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to guide future nature conservation activities.
The study conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will track dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown Langohr and aquatic bats in Inverewe Garden in West Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the plot to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
In a sound analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and the species is determined.
Next, a map and a habitat report are created to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to obtain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to loss of living space.
Windwheels and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by house cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their ears are more useful because of their nocturnal hunting habits than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland takes the theme of bats very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who carry out regular examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even set up Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave plant in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Property manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threeave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we do not yet know about bats, so here and on other goods we are doing these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, since it was possible that the unwanted destruction of a single nesting area could kill up to 400 females and juveniles and destroy the entire population on site.
Bats are under protection and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: 'We still have to learn a lot about bats and in many of our species we do not know how their populations are.'
