The opening ointments of the trade war between the USA and China were deafening. Although the battle is not over for a long time, Beijing could benefit from a long-term digging between the countries, my experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, fired the first warning at the beginning of the year when he imposed penalties on important Chinese exports, including solar cells, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new penalties for goods worth 200 billion dollars, effectively affecting half of all goods imported into the US from China.
Beijing struck in the same way each time and recently imposed fines of five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China has sworn to respond to any measure taken by the United States and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economic power will soon stumble.
Moving Washington to interfere would mean yielding. However, a public intrusion towards the US would be far too shameful for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays out its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries either in Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized," says Abigail Grace, a scientific assistant who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, says the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by the war for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government rebuilt the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to reverse normality.
All conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
A further six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 in the Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup since 1993 in Europe.
Europe won the crown back after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
The American star Phil Mikkelson, who had problems over most of the tournament, lowered his drop on the 16th course (par 3) in the water and lost against Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of four players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Paulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran from eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to win back the trophy.
It's about the team and I'm happy to have contributed," says the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passed on the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won the singles against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1.
I am so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I have been following on television since my childhood," says 23-year-old Ramm.
Woods lost all his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the biggest players of all time who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
The team USA had all weekend problems finding the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have performed high-quality performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the boys, they’ve fought.
There was a time this morning when we put Europe under pressure.
We didn't do anything about it.
