I love those 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated."
Update to the Red Age: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, the flowering conditions are recorded in a way that indicates decreasing concentrations.
A red algal flower extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinella to the south of the district of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough district, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
Last week, average concentrations on or off the Pinellas district were reported, low to high concentrations off the Manatee district, background to high concentrations on or off the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations on or off the Lee district and low concentrations in Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinella, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no new respiratory problems were reported during the past week.
